\f0\b\fs32 \cf0 Here are the standard ease types available in CSS:\
\pard\pardeftab560\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls1\ilvl0
\f2\b0\fs18 \cf0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f1\fs26 ease: This is the default value. It creates a transition that starts slowly, accelerates in the middle, and then slows down towards the end. It's represented by cubic-bezier(0.25, 0.1, 0.25, 1). \uc0\u8232 \u8232 \
\ls1\ilvl0
\f2\fs18 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f1\fs26 linear: This creates a transition with a constant speed from start to finish. It's represented by cubic-bezier(0, 0, 1, 1). \uc0\u8232 \u8232 \
\ls1\ilvl0
\f2\fs18 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f1\fs26 ease-in: This creates a transition that starts slowly and then progressively speeds up until the end. It's represented by cubic-bezier(0.42, 0, 1, 1). \uc0\u8232 \u8232 \
\ls1\ilvl0
\f2\fs18 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f1\fs26 ease-out: This creates a transition that starts abruptly and then progressively slows down towards the end. It's represented by cubic-bezier(0, 0, 0.58, 1).\'a0\uc0\u8232 \u8232 \u8232 \u8232 \
\ls1\ilvl0
\f2\fs18 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f1\fs26 ease-in-out: This creates a transition that starts slowly, speeds up in the middle, and then slows down again towards the end. It's represented by cubic-bezier(0.42, 0, 0.58, 1). \uc0\u8232 \u8232 \
\ls1\ilvl0
\f2\fs18 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\f1\fs26 cubic-bezier(n, n, n, n): This allows for the creation of a custom easing curve by specifying four numerical values that define the coordinates of two control points for a cubic Bezier curve. The x-coordinates must be within the range [0, 1].\'a0\
\pard\pardeftab560\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls1\ilvl1
\f2\fs18 \cf0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://cubic-bezier.com/"}}{\fldrslt 
\f1\fs26 https://cubic-bezier.com/}}
\f1\fs26  to customise the curve or simply inspect.\uc0\u8232 \u8232 \u8232 \
